      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">ING as a Hook and Word Extension</h2>

      <p>One of the most powerful uses of -ING is extending words already on the board. If your opponent plays PLAY, you can extend it to PLAYING for a much higher score — especially if the extension reaches a premium square.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Extend existing plays:</span> Look for verbs on the board that accept -ING. JUMP → JUMPING, DRAW → DRAWING, FISH → FISHING. You score the full extended word plus any crosswords formed.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Target premium squares:</span> If a verb ends 3 squares before a Triple Word Score, adding ING places the G on the premium square. Plan your extensions to hit multipliers.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Block opponent extensions:</span> If you see a verb positioned near premiums, play your own ING extension first — or block the lane entirely. Don't gift free extensions.</p>
        </div>
